===Noun===
{{en-noun|~|safeties}}

# The condition or feeling of being [[safe]]; [[security]]; [[certainty]].
#: ''If you push it to the limit, '''safety''' is not guaranteed.''
#* {{quote-av|en||date=May 15 2016|{{w|John Oliver}}|{{w|Last Week Tonight with John Oliver}}|3|12|episode=911|network=HBO||Oh, oh! “Go to '''safety'''”! Why didn’t I think of that⁉ Here I am in danger when, really, I could simply be going to '''safety'''! I shouldn’t have wasted your time by calling in the first place!}}
# {{lb|en|mechanics}} A [[mechanism]] on a weapon or dangerous [[equipment]] designed to prevent [[accidental]] firing.
#: ''Be sure that the '''safety''' is set before proceeding.''
# {{lb|en|American football}} An instance of a player being [[sacked]] or [[tackled]] in the end zone, or stepping out of the end zone and off the field, resulting in two points to the opposite [[team]].
#: ''He sacked the quarterback in the end zone for a '''safety'''.''
# {{lb|en|American football}} Any of the defensive [[players]] who are in [[position]] furthest from the line of [[scrimmage]] and whose responsibility is to [[defend]] [[against]] passes as well as to be the tacklers of last resort.
#: ''The free '''safety''' made a game-saving tackle on the runner who had broken past the linebackers.''
# {{lb|en|baseball}} A [[safety squeeze]].
#* '''1952''', {{w|Bernard Malamud}}, ''{{w|The Natural}}'', Time Life Books, 1966, p.{{nbsp}}225,<sup>[https://archive.org/details/thenatural00mala]</sup>
#*: Boy wondered about that bunt. He had a notion Fowler would commit himself soon because time was on the go. But Fowler didn’t, making it another sweep of three Pirates. He had thus far given up only two '''safeties'''.
# Preservation from escape; close custody.
#* {{circa|1596}} {{w|William Shakespeare}}, ''{{w|King John (play)|King John}}'', Act IV, Scene 2<sup>[http://www.opensourceshakespeare.org/views/plays/play_view.php?WorkID=kingjohn&Scope=entire&pleasewait=1&msg=pl]</sup>
#*: {{...}} imprison him, {{...}} / Deliver him to '''safety'''; and return,
# {{lb|en|dated}} A [[safety bicycle]].
#* '''1897''', ''American Architect and Architecture'' (volumes 57-58, page 51)
#*: Many wheelmen and wheelwomen, riding '''safeties''', tandems and tricycles, stopped there during the evening and we had good opportunity for comparing American and English bicycles {{...}}

